TE3 – Tunnelling Operation and Impact Assessment
TE3 – Tunnelling Operation and Impact Assessment
This is the third module of a three-module course that prepares candidates for the Specialist Registration Examination in Tunnel Engineering.
This is the third module of a three-module course that prepares candidates for the Specialist Registration Examinations in Tunnel Engineering.
TE1 – Geology of Singapore and Tunnel Design
TE3 – Tunnelling Operation and Impact Assessment
TE1 is not a prerequisite for TE2 and TE3. TE2 is not a prerequisite for TE3.
Theory and Application of Excavation Management System
Slurry quality and treatment for mechanized tunnelling
Case History for Mechanised and Conventional Tunnelling
Instrumentation & Monitoring for Mechanised and Conventional Tunnelling Works
Mechanical & Electrical Systems of Tunnel Boring Machines
Refer to “Guidelines to Sit for Specialist Registration Examination and Register as Specialist Professional Engineer in the Specialized Branch of Tunnelling Engineering (Oct 2020)”:
Civil engineers who are registered professional engineers with the Professional Engineers Board Singapore (PEB) and who wish to be certified as Specialist in Tunnel Engineering
Engineers who are involved with tunnel constructions such as geotechnical engineers, civil engineers, site engineers, field engineers, project engineers and construction managers
This course is relevant and useful for engineers who wish to embark on a career in the tunnelling industry.
Theory and Application of Excavation Management System
Theoretical basis of Excavation Management System (EMS) based on Total
Volume, Total Mass, Dry Mass/Dry Volume.
Primary and secondary EMS for Slurry and EPB TBMs
Measuring devices (flowmeters, density meters) installation, calibration and how it affects the EMS.
Slurry Quality and Treatment for Mechanised Tunnelling
Primary and Secondary functions of slurry in tunnelling
Physical and Rheological properties of bentonite-based slurry and how they affect the slurry functions
Planning of slurry Key Performance Indicators (KPIs) for different ground conditions and tunnelling operations
Slurry Treatment Plant Design (in-line, off-line), and understanding of STP flow diagrams.
An overview on the planning of Tunnelling KPIs including consideration on deep tunnels VS shallow tunnels.
Calculation methods for Maximum Thrusts, Maximum Torque, Tail void pressure, primary grout volumes.
Planning for Cutterhead Interventions (CHI) with the aid of wear prediction methods
Materials used for soil conditioning in EPB tunnelling and performance requirements
Testing methods for the evaluation of the suitability of foams
Correlation between types of soil conditioning and different types of ground conditions
Risks and mitigation measures related to soil conditioning in difficult ground conditions
Case history for mechanised and conventional tunnelling
Instrumentation and Monitoring for Mechanised and Conventional Tunnelling Works
Common types of instruments and how they work
Minimum monitoring requirements for tunnelling works
Special Monitoring Scenario (TBM launch & Initial Drive, Cutter Head Intervention, Mining/SCL)
Review Levels and Interpretation of Data
Estimating adjacent structure movements, including influence of building stiffness.
Damage classification and potential to cause building damage
Approach and framework for building impact assessment
Establishing allowable movement limits for buildings and defining monitoring review levels.
Mitigation Measures such as strengthening, underpinning, groundwater control, and other mitigation and contingency measures
Mechanical and Electrical Systems of Tunnel Boring Machines
Installation and operation of supporting mechanical and electrical systems for the TBM
Requirements for Factory Acceptance Testing and Site Acceptance Testing
Assistant Professor, Engineering, Singapore Institute of Technology
Assistant Professor, Engineering, Singapore Institute of Technology

Dr. Yeo Chong Hun teaches vector calculus, differential equations, numerical methods, linear algebra, ground improvement, soil behaviour and finite element method. His research background include tunnel heading stability, ground shock, liquefaction and deep mixing. He has extensive experience in soil tests, field instrumentation, physical modelling and numerical modelling. He is a technical assessor in the fields of soil tests, rock tests and pile tests. In the area of teaching, he is designing applied methods in the teaching and learning of engineering mathematics. His present research interest is in advanced soil tests and geotechnical model tests.
Deputy Director, Tunnelling, Land Transport Authority
Deputy Director, Tunnelling, Land Transport Authority

Massimo is a Chartered Civil Engineer (CEng MICE, MIES, MIEAust) holding an MSc (Civil Engineering & Construction Management) from Heriot Watt University and a GC (Geotechnical Engineering) from the National University of Singapore. After his first overseas tunnelling experience in the east (1996-1997), he moved to Taiwan working as a site/technical manager for construction companies. He was involved in major infrastructure projects such as the East Coast Railway, 2nd Freeway, Hydropower Plant & High-Speed Railway) and experienced in mined tunnelling characterised by difficult ground, large cross sections (up to 170 m2), and high overburden (over 500m). In Singapore since 2006, he has worked on tunnelling for Circle Line, Downtown Line, Cable Tunnel (independent reviewer), Thomson-East Coast Line and the upcoming Cross Island Line.

Since 2014, he has been serving as a committee member/honorary secretary of the Tunnelling and Underground Construction Society of Singapore. His areas of interest and expertise are mined tunnelling in soft ground, ground improvement, excavation management system, and slurry quality & treatment for mechanised tunnelling.
Principal Project Manager, Tunnelling, Land Transport Authority
Principal Project Manager, Tunnelling, Land Transport Authority

Antonio obtained his MSc in Geotechnical Engineering from the Complutensian University of Madrid and his MSc in Geology from the University of Salamanca. This combination allows him to appreciate the risks of underground design and construction with a holistic approach. He has almost 20 years of experience in Geotechnics and Tunnelling, from different projects in Spain and Singapore.  He has worked in almost all the branches of the Geotechnical Engineering, including Laboratory and In-situ testing, Forensic Engineering, Foundations, Underground Civil Structures and also Roads and High Speed Rail. In Singapore since 2013, he worked on Downtown Line 3, Thomson East Coast Line and currently working on the Thomson East Coast Line Extension and on the upcoming Cross Island Line. Antonio specialises in mechanised tunnelling and pipe jacking. His area of interest and expertise are Soil Conditioning, Drilling Fluids and Excavation Management, fields where he conducted investigations and published technical papers.
Deputy Director, Tunnelling; Assistant Chief Specialist (Mechanised Tunnelling); Land Transport Authority
Deputy Director, Tunnelling; Assistant Chief Specialist (Mechanised Tunnelling); Land Transport Authority

Chee Keong joined the Land Transport Authority (LTA) in 2002. He graduated with a 2nd Class Honours from the Nanyang Technological University of Singapore (NTU). He is currently a Principal Project Manager in LTA and holds a concurrent position as the Assistant Chief Specialist (Mechanised Tunnelling). At the core, Chee Keong is a passionate tunnelling engineer. After successfully managing and completing LTA tunnelling projects up till 2012, he was handpicked and seconded full time to Singapore Power for its very challenging cable tunnel project. Upon the landmark completion of the tunnelling works for the cable tunnel project, he was again seconded to PUB’s DTSS2 project before returning to LTA in 2019. The practical exposure to and tunnelling experience in varied and demanding ground conditions in Singapore has equipped and enabled him to harness a healthy appreciation of the different types of tunnelling methods and tunnel boring machines (TBMs).
Director, Civil Design, and Deputy Chief Specialist, Ground Engineering, Land Transport Authority
Director, Civil Design, and Deputy Chief Specialist, Ground Engineering, Land Transport Authority

Mr. Jeyatharan obtained his Bachelor of Science from the University of Peradeniya, Sri Lanka and received his doctorate from the University of Cambridge. He has worked with few consultants designing major infrastructure for about 10 years before moving to Land Transport Authority to plan and manage designs of major infrastructure projects. He has over 30 years of geotechnical and tunnel engineering experience and has been involved in the design aspects of several road and rail infrastructure projects in Singapore, including site investigations and testing, geotechnical interpretation, earth retaining structures, tunnels, foundations, instrumentation and monitoring and ground improvement. He conducts technical studies on topics such as geotechnical interpretations of deep excavation and tunnelling works etc. and shares his findings regularly in local conferences and seminars.
PhD, PE(Civil), PE(Geo), CPEng; Group Director, Infrastructure Design & Engineering, Land Transport Authority
PhD, PE(Civil), PE(Geo), CPEng; Group Director, Infrastructure Design & Engineering, Land Transport Authority

Kok Hun obtained his Bachelor of Engineering and Masters of Engineering from the National University of Singapore, and received his doctorate from the University of Cambridge. He has about 20 years of geotechnical and tunnel engineering experience and has been involved in the design aspects of several road and rail infrastructure projects in Singapore, including site investigations and testing, geotechnical interpretation, foundations, earth retaining structures, and tunnels. He conducts technical studies on topics such as deep excavation and tunnelling effects, building impact assessment, pile foundations, etc. and shares his findings regularly in local conferences and seminars. He is registered as a professional engineer in civil engineering as well as a specialist professional engineer in geotechnical engineering in Singapore, and a chartered professional engineer.
2 Deputy Group Director, Rail (Mechanical & Electrical); Chief Specialist, Power Supply; Land Transport Authority; Head, Project Management Business Unit, MSI Global Pte Ltd;
2 Deputy Group Director, Rail (Mechanical & Electrical); Chief Specialist, Power Supply; Land Transport Authority; Head, Project Management Business Unit, MSI Global Pte Ltd;

Melvyn Thong has over 30 years of experience in design, supervision and project management of electrical and mechanical installation for power plants, industrial, commercial and institutional, road and railway transit projects. Over 20 years of experience in the design, supervision and project management of Singapore Road and Rapid Transit Systems having been involved in the Thomson East Coast Line (TEL), Downtown Line (DTL), Compass Line (NSEW Line) asset renewal, North East Line (NEL), Circle Line (CCL), Sengkang Punggol LRT (SPLRT), Bukit Panjang LRT (BPLRT) and future RTS and Road Tunnel network in Singapore. Melvyn has extensive experienced in the design and implementation of Mechanical and Electrical requirements for Roads and Rapid Transit Systems for RTS and LRT networks.
A certified Chartered Electrical Engineer (UK) and Professional Engineer in Singapore, Melvyn is a Licensed Electrical Engineering in Singapore for design (unlimited voltage levels) and for electrical safety switching (up to 22kV). He has also contributed in development and review of many international and local standards such as the CP for fire safety for RTS and Roads, NFPA 502, etc.
As Head of Business Unit in MSI Global Pte Ltd, have successfully delivered technical support to clients from Japan, Malaysia and Singaporean, regional and international projects in Egypt, Dubai, Vietnam and Malaysia. Currently, he is also the Project Manager leading the independent Design Verification Engineer scope for the Doha MRT project that is now in revenue service.
Consultant, Mechanical Services; Systems Specialists; Rail / Road Systems Group; Land Transport Authority
Consultant, Mechanical Services; Systems Specialists; Rail / Road Systems Group; Land Transport Authority

Charlie Lim Lean Wan has more than 43 years of working experience in mechanical services such as tunnel ventilation system (TVS), environmental control system (ECS) and fire protection system. He is a registered Professional Engineer (Mechanical Engineering) and a Chartered Engineer (Railway Systems) in Singapore. He has been involved in the design of the mechanical services for the Singapore rail and road infrastructure projects. He also led the in-house teams in the design of the TVS for some of the rail and road infrastructure projects and was the qualified person for these projects. He also worked for 7 years at Singapore MRT Limited, where he was responsible for the maintenance of the ECS and TVS for the NSEW Line. His current responsibilities include the provision of specialist advice, spearheading research and development, and maintaining standards pertaining to mechanical services. His responsibilities also include conducting training for the LTA and operators’ staff on mechanical services on behalf of the Land Transport Authority, LTA Academy, and Singapore Rail Academy.
Principal Engineer, Building and Construction Authority
Principal Engineer, Building and Construction Authority

Er. Chow Wei Mun is presently a principal engineer in the Building and Construction Authority (BCA) of Singapore. He is a registered Professional Engineer (Civil) in Singapore. He has over 25 years of design and construction experience in various aspects of geotechnical engineering including instrumentation and monitoring, deep excavation, foundation and tunnelling. He is currently with the Geotechnical Engineering Department in BCA whose work is to regulate, conduct studies, and formulate policy to shape the industry towards safe design and construction of deep excavations, foundation and tunnelling in Singapore.

Er. Chow obtained his Bachelor and Master of Engineering degrees in Geotechnical Engineering from the National University of Singapore in 1997 and 2000 respectively. He had worked with consulting firms on feasibility studies, detailed design, and supervision of major infrastructure projects for about 15 years before joining BCA.
